\cf0 I felt truly unsafe and vulnerable as a kid in Kyrgyzstan. I was constantly looking over my shoulder, constantly worried about kids jumping me. Having to actually get in to fights to defend myself. Feeling like I had a target on my back. The closest thing to this that would map to conventional experiences would be that of bullying, yet I don\'92t really ever think of myself as having been bullied even though ithats probably a true statement. That sense of vulnerability, that sense that my parents didn\'92t understand it or respond to it probably had much bigger impact than I have probably imagined.\
